{
  "answer": "**Chapter 5 of the *Viṣṇu Smṛti* prescribes the punishment for a Brāhmaṇa's theft.**\n\nThis chapter outlines punishments for major sins (*mahāpātakas*), stating that while others face death, a Brāhmaṇa faces no corporal punishment but shall be branded (with specific marks for each sin) and banished from the country.[^1] Specifically, for theft (*steya*), the Brāhmaṇa \"shall [have] the mark of a dog's foot\" branded.[^2] General theft punishments (e.g., fines or limb amputation for large thefts) apply later in the chapter but are not for Brāhmaṇas, given the explicit exemption from corporal punishment.[^3]\n\nNo other chapters address this directly; Chapter 37 merely lists theft as a minor sin (*upapātaka*) without Brāhmaṇa-specific penalties.[^4]\n\n[^1]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, Chapter 5, [translation](/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/05/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti* 5.6, [paragraph](/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/05/translation/#p-8d4644).\n\n[^3]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti* 5.2 and 5.81–82, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/05/translation/#p-a40d4c).\n\n[^4]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, Chapter 37, [translation](/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/37/translation/).",
